option.value:
What we'll do - Give a short checklist of the most common causes why a .feature file isn't binding to step definitions. - Provide a minimal, working example (runner, step definition, feature) that you can drop into your project to verify binding. - Give commands and a small pinned dependency set to run/verify locally and a prioritized troubleshooting checklist.
Assumptions (explicit) - You're using Cucumber JVM with Java and JUnit (based on your workspace). If you're using JUnit 5 / Cucumber Platform Engine, tell me and I'll show that variant. - Package names and file paths follow the workspace you showed (org.satya.*).
Quick checklist — verify these first (common root causes) 1. Glue package mismatch: @CucumberOptions(glue = "...") must match the package of your step def class exactly (case-sensitive). 2. Runner not executed: ensure you're running the Runner class (not mvn test that runs other tests only) or configure surefire to pick it. 3. Wrong imports / annotation types: step defs must use io.cucumber.java.en.Given/When/Then (Cucumber v6+) or cucumber.api.java.en.* (older). Use the import that matches your Cucumber version. 4. Feature path: @CucumberOptions(features = "src/test/features") or correct relative path; ensure feature file is not under resources/test/resources unexpected path. 5. Step text mismatch: text in .feature must match the regex/Cucumber expression in the step method (watch punctuation, whitespace). 6. Encoding / BOM / CRLF issues: remove BOM and verify file encoding UTF-8. 7. Duplicate step definitions or parameter type mismatch can cause binding confusion — check console for "undefined steps" vs "ambiguous" errors. 8. Classpath: step definition class must be compiled and in test classpath (located under src/test/java).
Working example you can paste into your project to verify binding - Files mentioned below are linked to your workspace paths: - [MapsRunner.java](src/test/java/org/satya/runners/MapsRunner.java) - [MapsAPIStepDef.java](src/test/java/org/satya/stepDefinitions/MapsAPIStepDef.java) - [mapsAPI.feature](src/test/features/mapsAPI.feature) - [pom.xml](pom.xml) (recommended dependency block)
Java runner (JUnit4 + Cucumber) — drop into src/test/java/org/satya/runners/ ```Java::MapsRunner.java::src/test/java/org/satya/runners/MapsRunner.java package org.satya.runners;
import org.junit.runner.RunWith; import io.cucumber.junit.Cucumber; import io.cucumber.junit.CucumberOptions;
@RunWith(Cucumber.class) @CucumberOptions( features = "src/test/features", // path to feature files glue = {"org.satya.stepDefinitions"}, // package containing step definitions plugin = {"pretty", "html:target/cucumber-report"}, strict = true, monochrome = true ) public class MapsRunner { // empty - JUnit runner class } ```
Step definitions — drop into src/test/java/org/satya/stepDefinitions/ ```Java::MapsAPIStepDef.java::src/test/java/org/satya/stepDefinitions/MapsAPIStepDef.java package org.satya.stepDefinitions;
import io.cucumber.java.en.Given; import io.cucumber.java.en.When; import io.cucumber.java.en.Then; import static org.junit.Assert.*;
public class MapsAPIStepDef {
@Given("a valid AddPlace JSON body") public void a_valid_AddPlace_JSON_body() { // minimal stub for binding test System.out.println("Given: a valid AddPlace JSON body"); }
@When("I call AddPlace API") public void i_call_AddPlace_API() { System.out.println("When: I call AddPlace API"); }
@Then("the response status should be {int}") public void the_response_status_should_be(Integer status) { System.out.println("Then: response status should be " + status); // Dummy assertion to show test runs; replace with actual API call assertions assertTrue(status >= 100 && status < 600); } } ```
Feature file — drop into src/test/features/ ```gherkin::mapsAPI.feature::src/test/features/mapsAPI.feature Feature: Maps API bindings test
Scenario: Add place happy path Given a valid AddPlace JSON body When I call AddPlace API Then the response status should be 200 ```
Recommended minimal dependencies (pin versions) — add to your [pom.xml](pom.xml) ```XML::pom.xml::pom.xml <!-- Minimal dependency snippet for Cucumber + JUnit4 --> <project xmlns="http://maven.apache.org/POM/4.0.0" ...> <modelVersion>4.0.0</modelVersion> <groupId>org.satya</groupId> <artifactId>MapsApi</artifactId> <version>1.0-SNAPSHOT</version>
<dependencies> <!-- Cucumber JVM --> <dependency> <groupId>io.cucumber</groupId> <artifactId>cucumber-java</artifactId> <version>7.11.0</version> <scope>test</scope> </dependency> <dependency> <groupId>io.cucumber</groupId> <artifactId>cucumber-junit</artifactId> <version>7.11.0</version> <scope>test</scope> </dependency>
<!-- JUnit 4 --> <dependency> <groupId>junit</groupId> <artifactId>junit</artifactId> <version>4.13.2</version> <scope>test</scope> </dependency> </dependencies>
<build> <plugins> <!-- surefire plugin for running tests --> <plugin> <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId> <artifactId>maven-surefire-plugin</artifactId> <version>3.0.0-M9</version> </plugin> </plugins> </build> </project> ```
Run the runner locally (single command) - Run only the runner using Maven: ```bash::run-tests.sh::scripts/run-tests.sh mvn -Dtest=org.satya.runners.MapsRunner test ```
Expected minimal console output (binding successful) - You should see Cucumber running and the steps printed (from our System.out lines) and no "Undefined step" or "You can implement it using the snippet below" messages. If the console shows "Undefined step", it means the step text didn't match the annotation or the glue package is wrong.
Prioritized troubleshooting steps (if still not binding) 1. Verify glue package exactly: - Open [MapsRunner.java](src/test/java/org/satya/runners/MapsRunner.java) and ensure glue contains "org.satya.stepDefinitions". - Open [MapsAPIStepDef.java](src/test/java/org/satya/stepDefinitions/MapsAPIStepDef.java) and verify package declaration is exactly "package org.satya.stepDefinitions;". 2. Check annotation imports: - Step defs must import io.cucumber.java.en.* (for Cucumber v4+/v5+/v6+/v7+). If using older cucumber-api packages, update imports or upgrade Cucumber. 3. Confirm feature file path: - The runner uses features = "src/test/features" — confirm [mapsAPI.feature](src/test/features/mapsAPI.feature) sits there and is UTF-8 without BOM. 4. Ensure method regex/expression matches step text: - Plain text must match; a small difference (extra punctuation/capitalization) will cause undefined. - Consider using Cucumber expressions (e.g., "the response status should be {int}") as in the example. 5. Clean + rebuild: - mvn clean test 6. Check console for "Ambiguous step" (means more than one matching step) — then de-duplicate. 7. If using JUnit5, ensure you use the Cucumber JUnit Platform Engine instead of @RunWith; the runner example above is JUnit4 only. 8. If using an IDE (IntelliJ/Eclipse), ensure the test runner configuration is pointing to the JUnit runner class (MapsRunner) and that tests are compiled.
Why these choices / trade-offs (short) - Using JUnit4 runner @RunWith(Cucumber.class) is the simplest and very commonly used pattern — it keeps configuration straightforward and matches many existing projects. - Pinned Cucumber 7.x ensures modern io.cucumber.java.* API; if you use JUnit5, you must migrate to the platform engine (different setup). - Minimal feature + step defs show binding separately from your application logic (so you can isolate the binding problem).
If you'd like, I can: - Inspect your current [MapsRunner.java](src/test/java/org/satya/runners/MapsRunner.java), [MapsAPIStepDef.java](src/test/java/org/satya/stepDefinitions/MapsAPIStepDef.java), and [mapsAPI.feature](src/test/features/mapsAPI.feature) and point out exact mismatches. Ask one quick question only if you want me to check your actual files: do you want me to analyze your current files now? (Yes/No)
